@database TREE
@node MAIN
@title "Tree 1.10 ˋ Walter Weber-GroÔ, 1997"

   @{u}NAME@{uu}
   
      Tree
   
   @{u}FUNCTION@{uu}
   
      Shows directory tree
      
   @{u}FORMAT@{uu}
   
      Tree [[DIR=] directory] [FILES] [LEVEL=<0..84>]
            [WIDTH=<0..n>] [NOGRAF] [ANSI] [GRAFCOL=<0..7>]
            [DIRCOL=<0..7>] [FILECOL=<0..7>]]
      
   @{u}TEMPLATE@{uu}
   
      Tree DIR,FILES/S,LEVEL/K/N,WIDTH/K/N,NOGRAF/S,ANSI/S,
           GRAFCOL,DIRCOL,FILECOL
   
   @{"DESCRIPTION  " link DESCRIPTION} How does it work
   @{"NOTES        " link NOTES} Tips & Tricks
   @{"COPYRIGHT    " link COPYRIGHT} It's FREEWARE
   @{"AUTHOR       " link AUTHOR} It's me ;)

@endnode

@node DESCRIPTION "How does it work"

   Tree shows the directory tree of the named or current
   directory and (optionally) displays the names and sizes
   of all files and subdirectories in it.
   
   If @{b}FILES@{ub} is set, files and their sizes are displayed
   additionally. Wether this parameter is set or not,
   directories are always listed with their full sizes.
   
   The parameter @{b}LEVEL@{ub} requires a numeric value ranging from 0
   to the maximum value of 84, which is the default value. This
   parameter tells Tree how much directory levels shall be
   displayed.
   Independent of this value the size of all containing files and
   directories are evaluated.
   A value of 0 displays only the named root directory with its
   full size.
   
   @{b}WIDTH@{ub} requires a numeric value ranging from 0 to n. It tells
   Tree the maximum width of a @{i}displayed@{ui} file or directory name.
   Default value is 40.
   
   To avoid displaying the graphical tree characters such as 'ñ'
   or '-', you have to set the switch @{b}NOGRAF.@{ub}
   
   ANSI color display is switched on with @{b}ANSI@{ub}. If it is not
   set, the following parameters don't show any effect:
   
   - @{b}GRAFCOL@{ub} requires a numeric value ranging from 0 to 7 and
     refers to the color the graphical tree characters shall be drawn
     with. Default value is @{fg fill}3.@{fg text}
   
   - @{b}DIRCOL@{ub} also requires a numeric value ranging from 0 to 7
     and refers to the color in which the directory names are drawn.
     Default value is @{fg highlight}2.@{fg text}
   
   - @{b}FILECOL@{ub} also requires a numeric value ranging from 0 to 7
     and refers to the color the file names are displayed with.
     Default value is 1.
   
   Always the full directory size is evaluated, independent of how much
   information is displayed.
   
   
   @{b}EXAMPLE:@{ub}

   Ram Disk:>tree level 1 ansi
   @{fg highlight}Ram Disk@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg text}<log>@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg highlight}<tmp>@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg text}DEL                                 1356@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg text}PCD                                  322@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg text}Clipboards.info                     1019@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg text}ENV.info                            1019@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg text}T.info                              1019@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg text}Disk.info                           1243@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg highlight}ENV                               433391@{fg text} [21897]@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg highlight}Clipboards                            92@{fg fill}
   ñ- @{fg highlight}T                                      0@{fg fill}
   Ram Disk                             303957 @{fg text}[4346]


   @{b}NOTES:@{ub}

   File or directory links are displayed in acute brackets
   (see @{fg highlight}<tmp>@{fg text} and <log> in the above example) and their sizes
   are @{u}NOT@{uu} part of their parent directory's size and therefore
   have no size information displayed.
   
   So you get the real size of a directory.
   
   The number in square brackets displays the size of files
   of a directory which are not in any subdirectory, while
   the number before the first bracket refers to the full
   size of the directory. This difference will be displayed
   only if the switch @{i}FILES@{ui} is set.
   
@endnode

@node NOTES "Tips & Tricks"

   For just getting the size of a directory without listing the
   directory tree it is recommended to install an alias in your
   shell- or user-startup:
   
      @{fg fill}Alias Size Tree [] LEVEL 0@{fg text}
   
   To even list the files the following alias is useful:
   
      @{fg fill}Alias FTree Tree [] FILES ANSI@{fg text}
   
   Due to a missing paging function in Tree a batch file can serve
   for that purpose instead:
   
      @{fg fill}.KEY DIRNAME
      .BRA {
      .KET }
      
      Tree "{DIRNAME}" FILES ANSI >T:{$$}
      Sys:Utilities/Multiview T:{$$}
      Delete T:{$$} QUIET@{fg text}
   
   Please save these seven lines as "S:MTREE" and protect it with
   the "s" flag as follows to mark it as an executable file:
   
      @{fg fill}Protect S:MTREE +s@{fg text}
   
   Now you can type "MTREE [directory]" to list a directory tree
   that can be displayed pagewise.
   
   Also recommended is the use of the previous script as part of
   the workbench tools menue by using Stefan Becker's ToolMangager.
   Note that you have to mark the type of this menue entry as "CLI".
   
@endnode

